"{\"abstract\":\"Graph Neural Networks (GNNs) have been shown to be powerful in a wide range of graph-related tasks. While there exist various GNN models, a critical common ingredient is neighborhood aggregation, where the embedding of each node is updated by referring to the embedding of its neighbors. This paper aims to provide a better understanding of this mechanism by asking the following question: Is neighborhood aggregation always necessary and beneficial? In short, the answer is no. We carve out two conditions under which neighborhood aggregation is not helpful: (1) when a node\\u2019s neighbors are highly dissimilar and (2) when a node\\u2019s embedding is already similar to that of its neighbors. We propose novel metrics that quantitatively measure these two circumstances and integrate them into an Adaptive-layer module. Our experiments show that allowing for node-specific aggregation degrees have significant advantage over current GNNs.\",\"arxivId\":null,\"authors\":[{\"authorId\":\"81741645\",\"name\":\"Y. Xie\",\"url\":\"https://www.semanticscholar.org/author/81741645\"},{\"authorId\":\"145186923\",\"name\":\"Sha Li\",\"url\":\"https://www.semanticscholar.org/author/145186923\"},{\"authorId\":\"1390553618\",\"name\":\"Carl Yang\",\"url\":\"https://www.semanticscholar.org/author/1390553618\"},{\"authorId\":\"1723745\",\"name\":\"Raymond Chi-Wing Wong\",\"url\":\"https://www.semanticscholar.org/author/1723745\"},{\"authorId\":\"153034701\",\"name\":\"Jiawei Han\",\"url\":\"https://www.semanticscholar.org/author/153034701\"}],\"citationVelocity\":0,\"citations\":[],\"corpusId\":219326496,\"doi\":\"10.24963/ijcai.2020/181\",\"fieldsOfStudy\":[\"Computer Science\"],\"influentialCitationCount\":0,\"is_open_access\":true,\"is_publisher_licensed\":false,\"paperId\":\"1da4d11a5d36c7ded457fdb2a6435880e4c096cc\",\"references\":[{\"arxivId\":null,\"authors\":[{\"authorId\":\"3083609\",\"name\":\"Yifan Hou\"},{\"authorId\":\"47539059\",\"name\":\"Jinxin Zhang\"},{\